{"id":"mtrl-th/9603006","submitter":"Martin-D. Lacasse","authors":"Martin-Daniel Lacasse, Gary S. Grest, Dov Levine, T.G. Mason, and D.A.\n  Weitz","title":"A Model for the Elasticity of Compressed Emulsions","comments":"RevTeX with psfig-included figures and a galley macro","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1103/PhysRevLett.76.3448","report-no":null,"categories":"mtrl-th cond-mat.mtrl-sci","license":null,"abstract":"  We present a new model to describe the unusual elastic properties of\ncompressed emulsions. The response of a single droplet under compression is\ninvestigated numerically for different Wigner-Seitz cells. The response is\nsofter than harmonic, and depends on the coordination number of the droplet.\nUsing these results, we propose a new effective inter-droplet potential which\nis used to determine the elastic response of a monodisperse collection of\ndisordered droplets as a function of volume fraction. Our results are in\nexcellent agreement with recent experiments. This suggests that anharmonicity,\ntogether with disorder, are responsible for the quasi-linear increase of $G$\nand $\\Pi$ observed at $\\varphi_c$.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 12 Mar 1996 20:35:19 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-10-30"}
